I'm Josh Mait, Head of Marketing at Pavilion. I'm writing to pitch Sam Jacobs — our founder — as a guest for {{ podcast_name }}.

Sam spent 15+ years in high-pressure sales leadership roles — VP of Sales, CRO — at companies where the culture around performance, quota, and identity was relentless. He's talked publicly and candidly about the psychological toll of that environment: the anxiety, the identity collapse when deals fall through, and what it actually costs people who tie their self-worth to a number.

He eventually left, built Pavilion into a $200M professional community, and wrote "Kind Folks Finish First" (WSJ Bestseller) — which makes the case that the way most sales cultures are built is wrong, and that the operators who last are the ones who figured out how to be excellent without being ruthless.

Angles that resonate with wellness and mental health audiences:

• **The cost of quota culture** — what chronic high-pressure environments do to people over time, from someone who lived it for 15 years
• **The identity trap** — why so many operators struggle when performance dips, and how to separate self-worth from results
• **Kindness as a survival strategy** — his book's thesis isn't feel-good advice; it's a case that generosity and reciprocity produce better outcomes with less damage
• **What he's built differently at Pavilion** — a community where operators can be honest about struggle without career risk
• **Recovery and reinvention** — leaving corporate performance culture to bet on himself, and what that transition actually looked like

Sam speaks from personal experience, not theory. He's direct and doesn't dress it up.{% if sam_video_url %}

